Title: Tessting The Transfer Of Energy And Mass In Contact Binary Envelopes

PI: Prsa, Andrej - Villanova University

Type: LARGE

Summary: Contact binary stars are systems where the two stars are so close that they share a common envelope. They are ubiquitous, have short orbital periods (0.2-1.2 days) and large photometric amplitudes (20-50%). The distribution of mass ratios peaks at around 0.6, while effective temperatures of the stars are typically indistinguishable. Thus, stars of substantially different masses have the same temperatures. This points to the substantial mass and energy flow across the envelope that serves as a mixing agent, yet not a single model of contact binaries accounts for any mixing. We propose to introduce a mixing parameter into the model, fit the model to TESS data and explore mixing parameter correlations to infer the underpinnings of the physical processes that drive mass and energy transfer.
